<DOC><DOCNO> AP880801-0047 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-88 0549EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Crime     08-01 0313</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet-Crime,0325</SECOND><HEAD>More Murder And Assault Cases; 1,200 Officers Fired AfterCorruption Probe</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Violent crime in the Soviet capital is downoverall but murders, assaults and juvenile crime are on the riseand authorities probing police corruption have fired about 1,200people, an official said.   ``We don't hide that fact that in our ranks, there arebribe-takers, money-grubbers, common criminals in police uniform,''said Lt. Gen. P.S. Bogdanov, chief of Moscow's Administration ofInternal Affairs, which controls police affairs.   ``But we will not stop until our ranks have been cleansed,''Bogdanov told a recent news conference in remarks published Sundayby Komsomolskaya Pravda, the national youth daily.   He said that as a result of investigations in the first half of1988, about 1,200 Internal Affairs employees in Moscow were fired.   The official said that in the first six months of 1988, therewas a rise in murder, assault with intent to kill and assaultresulting in serious injury, compared to the same period last year.   The newspaper report gave no specific figures or reasons for thechange.   Bogdanov said, however, that the number of all crimes registeredin Moscow declined by 9.6 percent compared to 1987. Violent crime _excluding murder and assault _ dropped by 4.2 percent, he said.   He did not give the actual number of crimes registered.   In the first six months of 1988, Muscovites aged 18 and youngercommitted 25.6 percent of the crimes in the city, while juvenilecrime accounted for 22.6 percent of the city's unlawful acts duringthe same period in 1987, the police general said.   The juvenile crimes included robbery, rape, joyriding in someoneelse's car and apartment break-ins, he said.   Bogdanov said his ministry will continue to clean out corruptionin police ranks, a process begun more than a year ago under thereforms of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.</TEXT></DOC>